WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:04.510
&gt;&gt; Announcer: From the Library
of Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:04.510 --> 00:00:23.330
[ Silence ]

00:00:23.330 --> 00:00:25.190
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Well, we're
here at the Library of Congress.

00:00:25.190 --> 00:00:28.480
And we'll be talking with Yvette
Landry and Richard Comeaux

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:33.670 position:56%
and Beau Thomas who are Cajun and
honky tonk musicians from Louisiana.

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:34.970
My name is Steve Winick,

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:37.440
and I'm with the American
Folklife Center here

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:39.040
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:42.000
So, let's start out by
talking about a little bit

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:43.300
of what's been in the news lately.

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:45.380
You guy guys are from
Breaux Bridge I understand.

00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:46.810
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: We are.

00:00:46.810 --> 00:00:49.200
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: How's it
doing after the floods?

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:51.200
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: It's
been three and a half weeks

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:53.270
and we still have some water there.

00:00:53.270 --> 00:00:54.950
It's gone down a little
bit but it was pretty bad.

00:00:54.950 --> 00:00:57.510
I have to say it was pretty bad.

00:00:57.510 --> 00:00:59.990
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Are people,
are people managing to cope

00:00:59.990 --> 00:01:02.040
or has there been a lot
of evacuations there or?

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:03.340
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: No.

00:01:03.340 --> 00:01:04.640
People are managing to cope.

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:07.640
We, it kind of speaks
to our culture.

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:12.090
We don't, we don't really wait for
anybody to come in and help us.

00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:13.410
We just sort of do for ourselves.

00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:14.710
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:01:14.710 --> 00:01:16.010
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And where
we live everybody has a boat,

00:01:16.010 --> 00:01:17.310
everybody has an SUV.

00:01:17.310 --> 00:01:21.580
I mean everybody has
got, you know, something.

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:24.240
So, when the rain started and
the water started coming up,

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:25.640
people evacuated immediately.

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:29.010
You know, we had neighbor
helping neighbor kind of thing.

00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:32.590
And the cleanup has
been taking a while.

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:34.800
Some areas still have some
water and they can't get in yet.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:36.100
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:38.700
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: But slowly
getting back to normal, but, yeah.

00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:40.000
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: All right.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:41.300
Well, the rest of the
country is pulling for you.

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:42.600
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yes.

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:44.040 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And wishing for a
speedy recovery [multiple speakers].

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:46.730
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:
Talking about boats, I mean,

00:01:46.730 --> 00:01:49.370
I've never seen this ever.

00:01:49.370 --> 00:01:52.730
We have a drawbridge that
crosses the Bayou Teche.

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:57.020
The water was so high that
a guy got in his canoe

00:01:57.020 --> 00:01:58.540
and paddled across the drawbridge.

00:01:58.540 --> 00:01:59.840
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Over the bridge.

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:01.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Over the bridge.

00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:02.440
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Over the bridge.

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:03.740
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:
Never seen that ever.

00:02:03.740 --> 00:02:05.040
Ever.

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:06.340
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: It was about
two feet [multiple speakers].

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:07.640
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: May never
see that again, you know?

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:08.940
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Wow,
that's amazing.

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:10.240
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:11.540
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick:

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:12.840
Yeah. So, all right.

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:14.140
So, in that area, is it
mostly French culture?

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:16.440
Were you growing up
essentially bilingual?

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:19.380
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:
I'd say bilingual.

00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:21.970
I mean, the roots are Cajun.

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:23.270
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:02:23.270 --> 00:02:25.740 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Cajun, you know,
Acadians is what we're labeled as.

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:30.260
You know, exiled years ago from
Nova Scotia down to south Louisiana

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:33.480
and yes we are Acadians and Cajuns
is what we call ourselves short.

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:35.040
But we are bilingual.

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:37.070
I mean, we've all been
educated and whatever.

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:38.370
We can speak English too.

00:02:38.370 --> 00:02:39.670
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:02:39.670 --> 00:02:41.500
Right. Well, I mean my question
was more along the lines

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:43.400 position:56%
of whether all you also spoke French

00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:44.840
because not everybody
in Louisiana does.

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:46.140
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Well.

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:48.950
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And I'll speak
to that because Richard grew up,

00:02:48.950 --> 00:02:50.730
he speaks French fluently.

00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:52.820
I do not.

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:54.120
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: OK.

00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:55.420
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I was
the first in my family

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:56.770
and my brother to not speak French.

00:02:56.770 --> 00:03:01.150
And part of that comes from
when my parents were growing up,

00:03:01.150 --> 00:03:04.250
it was frowned upon to speak French
in school, so they got punished

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:05.610
for speaking French in school.

00:03:05.610 --> 00:03:09.870
So, they would only speak French
at home and they didn't teach us.

00:03:09.870 --> 00:03:12.730
And we were not taught
French in school.

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:15.900
So, some of my generation,
like Richard and others,

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:17.420
did pick up the language.

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:19.740
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: But it
was not until after school.

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:21.040
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Right
[multiple speakers].

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:22.340
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: You know,
after high school is when I learned

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:24.600
in a little community, Henderson,
right out of Breaux Bridge.

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:25.900
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:03:25.900 --> 00:03:27.210
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Most
people, that's all they spoke.

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:29.670
So, I had to kind of
just pick it up.

00:03:29.670 --> 00:03:30.970
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Right.

00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:32.270
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And so
was it true for all of you

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:34.700
that in school French
was kind of discouraged?

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:36.000
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: It was
not taught in school at all.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.300
It was not.

00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:40.490 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I learned it in the university
and through traveling and learned it

00:03:40.490 --> 00:03:43.200
through the music of my culture.

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:45.620
That's how I learned to speak and
to write a little bit of French,

00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:47.120 position:56%
but it was not encouraged in school.

00:03:47.120 --> 00:03:48.660
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: My
grandparents spoke French fluently

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:50.360
and my parents spoke
French fluently.

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:53.410
And they would speak to each other
in French when they didn't want us

00:03:53.410 --> 00:03:54.710
to know what was going on.

00:03:54.710 --> 00:03:56.010
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Us
to now what was going on.

00:03:56.010 --> 00:03:57.310
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:03:57.310 --> 00:03:58.610
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And
that's how that went.

00:03:58.610 --> 00:03:59.910
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So it
became the secret language.

00:03:59.910 --> 00:04:01.210
In other words, you
couldn't know it.

00:04:01.210 --> 00:04:02.510
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Exactly
[multiple speakers].

00:04:02.510 --> 00:04:03.810
Exactly.

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:05.110
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:04:05.110 --> 00:04:06.410
So, what was the music culture
like when you were growing up?

00:04:06.410 --> 00:04:07.710
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: It's probably
different for each one of us.

00:04:07.710 --> 00:04:09.010
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Different
for each one of us, you know?

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:10.310
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Yeah.

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:11.610
For sure.

00:04:11.610 --> 00:04:14.330
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: My grandparents
were musicians and they played sort

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:16.880
of a swing and what
would you call that?

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:18.180
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Dixieland.

00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:19.480
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Dixieland.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:20.780
Kind of Dixieland music.

00:04:20.780 --> 00:04:22.080
So, I heard a lot of
that growing up.

00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:23.610
Not necessarily them because
they had stopped playing

00:04:23.610 --> 00:04:25.460
by the time I came around.

00:04:25.460 --> 00:04:27.180
But recordings and country music.

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:28.700
That's what my family listened to.

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:30.400
We didn't really listen
to Cajun music.

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:32.010
Richard has a different story.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:33.310
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:

00:04:33.310 --> 00:04:34.960
And my influences were
strictly Cajun music.

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:38.260
My father was a Cajun musician.

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:39.930
Back then lap steel.

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:41.230
No pedals.

00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:42.530
Pedals weren't even invented yet.

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:46.320
He played just a six-string
lap steel with Cajun music,

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:49.800
and that's what I grew
up listening to.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:51.100
That's where I began.

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:52.400
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And Beau?

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:53.700
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: I don't
know where I come from.

00:04:53.700 --> 00:04:56.450
No one in my family for
ages back, generations,

00:04:56.450 --> 00:05:01.430
I cannot trace anyone back that
played any musical instruments.

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:04.040
But I grew up -- my family loved
Cajun music and our culture.

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:07.900
My family owns a Cajun food and
spice manufacturing company.

00:05:07.900 --> 00:05:10.050
So, we certainly knew
the culture and music,

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:11.350
but I didn't grow up with it.

00:05:11.350 --> 00:05:14.710
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I had some of the
greatest Cajun musicians playing

00:05:14.710 --> 00:05:16.780
at a restaurant in my back yard.

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:20.580
And until I started playing
Cajun music 12 years ago,

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:22.040
I didn't even know who they were.

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:27.070
You know, Dewey Balfa and Octa
Clark and all these guys played

00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:31.510
at a little restaurant called
Mulate's in Breaux Bridge and --

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:32.810
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:
[inaudible] Thibodaux.

00:05:32.810 --> 00:05:34.110
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: [inaudible]
Thibodaux.

00:05:34.110 --> 00:05:35.410
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Yeah
[multiple speakers].

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:36.710
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: I've been to
Mulate's [multiple speakers].

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:38.010
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And I didn't
even know who they were other

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:41.720
than there was some music going
on in the background [inaudible].

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:43.020
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:44.320
But you did hear it [inaudible].

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.450
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: But I did
hear it [multiple speakers].

00:05:46.450 --> 00:05:47.750
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Sure.

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:50.190
So, that was certainly one of the
contexts in which you'd see music.

00:05:50.190 --> 00:05:54.190
There was restaurants and dance
halls and that kind of thing.

00:05:54.190 --> 00:05:55.490
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Right.

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:58.510
And we used to go to some things
called, I remember the first time

00:05:58.510 --> 00:06:02.410
that I really took note
of it was at a boucherie,

00:06:02.410 --> 00:06:03.710
and that's where you
slaughtered the pig.

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:05.010
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:06:05.010 --> 00:06:06.310
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And then
all this stuff was made.

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:11.720
And there was a, it was probably
close to your house growing up,

00:06:11.720 --> 00:06:15.480
it has the, right by the overpass.

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:17.040
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Oh
by [multiple speakers].

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:19.060
That's where I learned
to play the steel guitar.

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:20.360
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Exactly.

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:21.660
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: At
his camp, matter of fact.

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:22.960
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And I
actually have a picture of me;

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:26.220
I'm probably about nine or ten
years old holding an accordion.

00:06:26.220 --> 00:06:29.300
You know, I've got a little skipper
hat on, you know, doing this.

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:33.530
But I remember people would just
break out instruments, everybody,

00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:36.910
you know, and you just
start this jam right there.

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:40.750
And so not only on the radio, or at
the restaurant, but it was pretty,

00:06:40.750 --> 00:06:42.520
I mean, common to go
to somebody's house

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:45.040
and somebody just started
playing music.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:46.340
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:06:46.340 --> 00:06:47.640
So, what was your first instrument?

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:48.940
Was it the accordion?

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:50.240
Or did you start?

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:51.540
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: No.

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:52.840
My first instrument was
the piano when I was three.

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:54.140
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: OK.

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:55.440
That's a good starting
place, isn't it?

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:56.740
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

00:06:56.740 --> 00:06:58.040
I started with piano
when I was three.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:06:59.340
And then when I was
in the fourth grade,

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:00.640
I started playing the clarinet.

00:07:00.640 --> 00:07:01.940
And through high school I ended

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:04.360
up playing all the
woodwind instruments.

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:08.190
And after high school
I closed the piano,

00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:10.830
closed all the other instruments
and said, "I hate this.

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:12.130
I don't like music.

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:13.760
I'm never doing it again."

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:15.060
Done.

00:07:15.060 --> 00:07:16.360
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Good
luck with that, right?

00:07:16.360 --> 00:07:17.660
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:18.960
Exactly.

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:20.260
And then 12 years ago,
I ended up going

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:22.120
in a totally different direction
and I bought a bass guitar

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:27.120
and somebody -- I was
just going to buy it to -

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:28.950
my dad was, my dad had cancer.

00:07:28.950 --> 00:07:32.370
And so it was just sort
of a therapy instrument.

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:33.670
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Sure.

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:34.970
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I was
just going to play it

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:36.270
at home and somebody said,

00:07:36.270 --> 00:07:39.430 position:56%
"Well, you know, there's a jam at
this little store down [inaudible]."

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:44.440
And I ended up going to that
jam and here I am [laughs].

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:46.040
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So,
you started with bass?

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:49.100
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Started with
bass and then I went to accordion.

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:55.130
And then when I first
experienced that first jam session,

00:07:55.130 --> 00:08:00.040
it was in an old house, which
they had converted into a store.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:01.410
And I opened the door.

00:08:01.410 --> 00:08:03.000
And there was this
back room probably

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:04.300
about the size of this stage.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:08.810
And they had maybe nine people
in there from the age of two

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:11.790
to 92, all just playing music.

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:13.280
And I just went, "Oh, wow.

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:14.580
What is this?"

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:17.380
You know? I had never
experienced anything like that.

00:08:17.380 --> 00:08:20.130
So, I started going and then I
got all excited and I just wanted

00:08:20.130 --> 00:08:22.440
to learn every instrument.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:24.170
So, I borrowed, I told my mom,

00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:26.380
I said I want to try
and learn accordion.

00:08:26.380 --> 00:08:27.810
So, she said, "Oh,

00:08:27.810 --> 00:08:29.440
I think [inaudible] brother
might have an accordion."

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:32.340
So, she called a friend
of a friend and got that.

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:36.400
And then I remember seeing a fiddle
on the wall in my mom's house.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:37.700
And I said, "What's that fiddle?"

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:39.090
She said, "Well, that's your
great grandfather's fiddle."

00:08:39.090 --> 00:08:42.600 position:56%
And I said, "Could I take that off
the wall and maybe try and do that?"

00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:44.060
So, you know, I got that.

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:47.060
And then a friend of
mine had a guitar.

00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:48.970
So, I started learning
all of them at once

00:08:48.970 --> 00:08:51.390 position:56%
but I stuck more with the accordion.

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:53.870
So, I was doing bass and accordion.

00:08:53.870 --> 00:08:58.190
And I tried fiddle.

00:08:58.190 --> 00:08:59.490
Not so much.

00:08:59.490 --> 00:09:00.790
Not so much.

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:02.090
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: What?

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:03.390 position:56%
But luckily you have, you have Beau.

00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:04.690
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: But
luckily I have him [laughter].

00:09:04.690 --> 00:09:06.110
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, tell us
about, Beaux tell us about your,

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:08.100
how you started with the fiddle.

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:11.550
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: I,
kind of out of nowhere.

00:09:11.550 --> 00:09:16.070
My family had this spice company
and we were doing a cochon de lait,

00:09:16.070 --> 00:09:18.430
roasting a little baby suckling pig

00:09:18.430 --> 00:09:21.630
for the Super Bowl Half
Time Show in New Orleans.

00:09:21.630 --> 00:09:22.930
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Excellent.

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:24.230
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: And
there was Dan Rather

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:27.700
and all these big guys walking
around in $5,000 and $10,000 suits

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:29.280
and piece of pig in
their hand, you know,

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:31.160
with a little grease
dripping down their chin.

00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:34.300
So, my dad said, "Hey,
boy," like the year before,

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:37.180
"if I get you a Cajun accordion
would you learn one or two songs

00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:40.540
and sit on the, by the pig
and play the accordion?"

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:43.160
I'm like sit by a pig
and play and accordion?

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:44.770
No, I don't know about that.

00:09:44.770 --> 00:09:47.610
And some little guy was with
my sister and said, "Hey Beau,

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:49.530
I bet you couldn't play a fiddle."

00:09:49.530 --> 00:09:51.830
I'm like, "Oh, I bet you I could."

00:09:51.830 --> 00:09:53.130
Well, anyway, I begged my dad.

00:09:53.130 --> 00:09:56.720 position:56%
Three months later he finally bought
me this fiddle out of nowhere.

00:09:56.720 --> 00:09:58.400
And I took it home.

00:09:58.400 --> 00:10:01.730
Within just a few hours
I came down playing four

00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:03.360
or five songs that I had learned.

00:10:03.360 --> 00:10:06.620
And five and a half months later
I went on my first tour half way

00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:08.620
around the world and
started playing.

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:10.210
That was 27 years ago
and never looked back.

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:11.510
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: All right.

00:10:11.510 --> 00:10:12.810
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Yeah.

00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:14.110
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, fiddle was
really your first instrument?

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:15.410
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: I think so.

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:16.710
Yeah.

00:10:16.710 --> 00:10:18.010
I mean, I played trumpet a little
bit in high school and drums

00:10:18.010 --> 00:10:19.310
in a very small band, but terrible.

00:10:19.310 --> 00:10:22.930
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: I remember
playing with him about that time

00:10:22.930 --> 00:10:25.760
and it's like he came out
of the womb with a fiddle.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:27.800
He played that good back then.

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:29.100
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:30.400
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:
He's amazing now.

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.740
But he was really, really
accomplished even back then.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:34.040
I mean [multiple speakers].

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:35.340
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: And I didn't play
as a kid [multiple speakers].

00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:36.930
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: We still talk
about that back home how he just

00:10:36.930 --> 00:10:39.210
like came out the womb
playing the fiddle.

00:10:39.210 --> 00:10:40.750
You know? Really.

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:42.050
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Amazing.

00:10:42.050 --> 00:10:47.000
And so, and you've said that
your first sort of influence was.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.300
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Was my
father [multiple speakers].

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:50.770
Yeah. My father played Cajun steel

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:55.080
but my very first instrument
was an acoustic guitar at four.

00:10:55.080 --> 00:11:00.060
And I just learned and I had just a
musically family on my dad's side.

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:02.560 position:56%
Every family reunion I couldn't wait

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:04.180
because I'd learn something
different.

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:08.220
You know, because I had my cousins
as mentors and they'd show me how

00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:12.480
to put my hands and then the ear
kind of took over and then got home

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:15.940
from school, 13 years old,
walked into my bedroom

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:21.680
and brand new pedal steel
guitar at the foot of my bed.

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:24.260
And my dad, and I'll
never forget this.

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:27.510
I turned around, looked at my dad,
and he just watched my whole move.

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:29.390
I said, "Hi, dad."

00:11:29.390 --> 00:11:31.540
Walk in from school with the
book sack and everything.

00:11:31.540 --> 00:11:34.150
And my dad is sitting and my
dad liked his beer, you know?

00:11:34.150 --> 00:11:37.040
So, he had his Schlitz beer
on the table like that.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:39.430
And he just watched me, just
around the corner like that.

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:42.290
And, again, when I walked
into my bedroom I just froze

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:45.310
and the book sack just fell.

00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:46.610
And I turned around.

00:11:46.610 --> 00:11:48.190
And he goes, "There you are.

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:49.740
I bought this for you."

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:51.260
And I'm like, I didn't
know the first thing

00:11:51.260 --> 00:11:52.810
about this thing but
it just sat there.

00:11:52.810 --> 00:11:54.440
He puts the picks on.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:55.920
He says, "Now listen."

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:57.870
He strums it and it's
just this triad tune.

00:11:57.870 --> 00:11:59.410
It's an open tuning.

00:11:59.410 --> 00:12:00.710
It made a chord.

00:12:00.710 --> 00:12:02.010
I'm like I recognize that chord.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:03.790
And he said, "Yep,
this one position.

00:12:03.790 --> 00:12:05.090
Here's another position.

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:07.990
Here." This is pretty much
basically how our Cajun music --

00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:09.670
these are the three
chords that you're going

00:12:09.670 --> 00:12:11.760
to play for a long, long time.

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:15.390
Didn't show me the picking but
then he gave me a couple people

00:12:15.390 --> 00:12:17.200
to just listen to.

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:21.000
And I went out and sought out
these, back then 45s and LPs,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.460
and I'd go to this camp where
she first got her accordion thing

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:26.290
at Ellis Trosclair's camp.

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:32.470
And I'd spin these records on
this stereo time and time --

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:33.770
I'd scratch it a little bit

00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:35.960
and put it back just to
emulate these sounds.

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:38.230
And, you know, that's how it came.

00:12:38.230 --> 00:12:42.810
And like Beau did with his fiddle,
it, my steel picking back then

00:12:42.810 --> 00:12:46.310
in four or five years I was
pretty much accomplished

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:49.310
on the Cajun side of the music.

00:12:49.310 --> 00:12:51.840
But then I got bored.

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:54.640
I wanted, there was more
music going through my head

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:59.120
until I discovered the
pedal steel guitar.

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:03.060
And when I heard it first I'm
like this is what I want to play

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:06.230
because the pedal steel guitar
goes in depth and you, you know,

00:13:06.230 --> 00:13:08.120
you tune it like a piano.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:09.420
You have the scale.

00:13:09.420 --> 00:13:11.030
You can play notes.

00:13:11.030 --> 00:13:12.910
Not just the triad.

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:16.980
And then I was mentored by this
man, Milton Gilbo from back home

00:13:16.980 --> 00:13:18.750
who was accomplished back then.

00:13:18.750 --> 00:13:21.800
And he just started teaching
me how this is structured.

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:24.360
I actually had to let
the Cajun music go.

00:13:24.360 --> 00:13:26.110
I had to put it in the garbage

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:27.960
because you've got
to think different.

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:31.280
You can't let this
chank-a-chank sound get in the way

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:33.940
with what you're trying to do
with the pedal steel guitar.

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:36.670
Well, then I found out about this
school in Nashville that goes

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:38.570
in depth and teaches
what all these pedals

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:40.650
and levers do within the tuning.

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:42.130
So, you take all this home.

00:13:42.130 --> 00:13:43.430
You don't learn it over there.

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:47.110
You've got to take it home
and spend thousands of hours

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:48.410
to get your hands in all that.

00:13:48.410 --> 00:13:51.410
Well, lo and behold it's
42 years later and I'm

00:13:51.410 --> 00:13:52.740
at the Library of Congress.

00:13:52.740 --> 00:13:54.480
Go figure, you know?

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:55.780
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:13:55.780 --> 00:13:57.520
So, you know, it's interesting
because I think a lot

00:13:57.520 --> 00:13:59.580
of people outside of Louisiana,

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:03.230
if they think about Cajun music
they'll certainly think about,

00:14:03.230 --> 00:14:04.820
you know, accordion and
they'll think of fiddle

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:07.050
and they'll think of
chank-a-chank guitar,

00:14:07.050 --> 00:14:11.070
but they won't necessarily think
of lap steel or pedal steel.

00:14:11.070 --> 00:14:12.800
But it was there.

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:14.100
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: It was.

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:15.400
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Oh, yes
[multiple speakers].

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:16.700
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: It was
prominent in the '60s is

00:14:16.700 --> 00:14:18.000
when I guess [multiple
speakers] and that's while.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:19.300
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: In
the Cajun dance halls

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:20.600
and night clubs is when
it began to emerge.

00:14:20.600 --> 00:14:21.900
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux:
And I play back home

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:23.700
with a group now called
High Performance

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:25.110
that has Steve Riley in the band.

00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:27.760
Everybody on the planet
knows who Steve Riley is.

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:29.060
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:30.360 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: But that makes--

00:14:30.360 --> 00:14:31.870
all our fathers played
together at one time or another.

00:14:31.870 --> 00:14:33.170
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:14:33.170 --> 00:14:34.470
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: We're
the second generation.

00:14:34.470 --> 00:14:37.060
So, it's called High Performance
and it's called Cajun music

00:14:37.060 --> 00:14:39.340
on steroids because it's powerful.

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:40.640
It's really good.

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:41.940
So.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:43.240
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:44.540
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: But I'm
playing pedal steel not open.

00:14:44.540 --> 00:14:45.840
I can emulate the same tones.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:49.160 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: But I will say not
too long ago I dug up an old record,

00:14:49.160 --> 00:14:51.770
I don't know where
it's at, and it was,

00:14:51.770 --> 00:14:54.880
you might have been 17 years
old playing on an open tuning.

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:56.180
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Yes.

00:14:56.180 --> 00:14:57.560
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Maybe
Jambalaya; it was fast.

00:14:57.560 --> 00:14:58.860
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Yes.

00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:00.160
Yeah.

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:01.460
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: It was really fast.

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:02.760
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Yeah.

00:15:02.760 --> 00:15:04.060
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: I'm not sure
if it was all the way open.

00:15:04.060 --> 00:15:05.360
You may have had a
pedal that brought it

00:15:05.360 --> 00:15:06.660
down the floor [multiple speakers].

00:15:06.660 --> 00:15:07.960
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: No.

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:09.260
No. It was open.

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:10.560
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: So, it
was, it was hopping.

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:11.860
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Just hopping.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:13.160
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: You might
have been 17 or something.

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:14.460
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Sixteen.

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:15.760
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Yeah.

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:17.060
You were fast.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:18.360
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: Yeah.

00:15:18.360 --> 00:15:19.660
Anyway.

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:20.960
&gt;&gt; Beau Thomas: Amazing.

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:22.260
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: So,
time goes, don't it?

00:15:22.260 --> 00:15:23.560
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:15:23.560 --> 00:15:24.860
It sure does.

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:26.160
So, Yvette, you mentioned that
one of the people who played

00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:27.460
at Mulate's while you were
growing up was Dewey Balfa, right?

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:28.760
And I know that you
played with Balfa Toujours.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:30.060
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Right.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:31.360
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So,
tell us about that.

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:32.660
About how that was sort of
being in that second generation.

00:15:32.660 --> 00:15:33.960
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Well, let me
tell you how I met Christine.

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:36.580 position:56%
She was living in Breaux Bridge at
the time and I was at the Winn Dixie

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:38.130
in Breaux Bridge checking out.

00:15:38.130 --> 00:15:40.740
And there was this girl
standing in front of me.

00:15:40.740 --> 00:15:42.670
And, you know, we just
like to talk to anybody.

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:43.970
We don't care.

00:15:43.970 --> 00:15:45.270
So, she's standing in front
of me and I said, "Hi."

00:15:45.270 --> 00:15:49.450
And she turned around
and she goes, "Oh, hi."

00:15:49.450 --> 00:15:50.750
And I said, "I'm Yvette.

00:15:50.750 --> 00:15:52.050
Who are you?"

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:53.350
And she said, "Well, I'm Christine.

00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:54.650
It's nice to meet you."

00:15:54.650 --> 00:15:57.040
And we're having this conversation
and I said, "Well, what do you do?"

00:15:57.040 --> 00:15:59.260
And she said, "Well,
I'm a musician."

00:15:59.260 --> 00:16:00.560
And I said, "Oh."

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:02.030
And I had just started
playing music.

00:16:02.030 --> 00:16:05.580
So, I said, "Oh, well, I'm
starting to play music too."

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:07.330 position:56%
And I said, "What's your last name?"

00:16:07.330 --> 00:16:08.690
She said, "Balfa."

00:16:08.690 --> 00:16:09.990 position:56%
And I said, "Oh, well, that's nice."

00:16:09.990 --> 00:16:11.290 position:56%
I said, "Well, you know, I'm playing

00:16:11.290 --> 00:16:12.990
with the Lafayette
Rhythm Devils right now.

00:16:12.990 --> 00:16:15.400
I started playing about
three months ago," and I'm,

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:16.700
you know, just doing this.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:18.000
And she'd say, "Oh that's nice.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:19.300
That's nice.

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:20.600
That's nice."

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:23.070
Still have no clue who Dewey Balfa
is or the importance of Dewey Balfa

00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:24.810
or who I'm talking
to at this moment.

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:27.790
You know, so she said,
"Oh, that's really nice."

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:30.550
She said, "You know, we're
doing a benefit for my sister,

00:16:30.550 --> 00:16:34.840
and if you'd like to come and play
bass guitar that would be great."

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:36.140
So, I said, "Sure."

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:37.680
You know, it was right
there in Breaux Bridge.

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:42.030
So, that Sunday I ended up going
to play with Balfa Toujours.

00:16:42.030 --> 00:16:43.330
Not a clue.

00:16:43.330 --> 00:16:44.650
I didn't know who Balfa
Toujours was.

00:16:44.650 --> 00:16:48.070
So, the next weekend I'm
talking to this little guy

00:16:48.070 --> 00:16:50.560
who started playing music the
same time as I did, and he said,

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:52.040
"So what did you do this weekend?"

00:16:52.040 --> 00:16:53.340
And I said, "Oh, I
played with this band.

00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:54.640
What's their name?

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:58.940
I think something like
Balfa something."

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:00.530
And he goes, "Balfa Toujours?

00:17:00.530 --> 00:17:01.830
You played with Balfa Toujours?"

00:17:01.830 --> 00:17:03.130
And I said, "Yeah."

00:17:03.130 --> 00:17:06.000
So, that's when I realized
maybe I should kind of go check

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.300
and see who these people are.

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:08.600
[laughter]

00:17:08.600 --> 00:17:12.810
But, no, it's incredible
to play with Christine.

00:17:12.810 --> 00:17:17.040
And she basically channels
her father in that music.

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:21.590
And if you close your eyes, you
could be in 2016 or you could be

00:17:21.590 --> 00:17:27.090
in 1956 or you could be in
18-- whatever, you know?

00:17:27.090 --> 00:17:28.390
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: You're right.

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:30.720
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: So, it's been
an incredible journey playing

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:32.130
with them.

00:17:32.130 --> 00:17:33.430
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:17:33.430 --> 00:17:35.220
I mean for a lot of
people outside Louisiana,

00:17:35.220 --> 00:17:38.090
Dewey Balfa would have been
the first Cajun musician

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:39.390
that they heard.

00:17:39.390 --> 00:17:40.690
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I think so.

00:17:40.690 --> 00:17:42.470
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Because he started
going to festivals in the '70s.

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:43.770
And that's, you know?

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.070
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: You're right.

00:17:45.070 --> 00:17:46.890
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Before that no one
really knew what Cajun music was

00:17:46.890 --> 00:17:48.830
outside Louisiana and
parts of Texas.

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:50.130
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Right.

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:51.430
And he was a bus driver.

00:17:51.430 --> 00:17:52.730
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:54.030
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I mean, you know?

00:17:54.030 --> 00:17:55.330
That's how people knew
him as basically.

00:17:55.330 --> 00:17:56.630
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:57.930
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: A bus driver
who played a little bit of music.

00:17:57.930 --> 00:17:59.230
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:17:59.230 --> 00:18:00.530
But the other thing that I was
always impressed with when talking

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:03.900 position:56%
to other musicians about Dewey Balfa
particularly was the way he was just

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:06.970
a mentor to so many people and
so many people learned from him.

00:18:06.970 --> 00:18:08.850
And so it's great that you
got to play with Christine

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:10.150
and you get to play with Christine.

00:18:10.150 --> 00:18:11.450
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:12.750
Yeah.

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:14.050
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Because she was,
you know, sort of the best student,

00:18:14.050 --> 00:18:15.350
the main student, you
know what I mean?

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:16.650
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Right.

00:18:16.650 --> 00:18:19.300
Absolutely.

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:23.900
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, you know,
the group that you played

00:18:23.900 --> 00:18:28.240
with today had those Cajun
influences but also does a lot

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:30.710
of what you call Louisiana
honky tonk.

00:18:30.710 --> 00:18:35.550
So, explain that, those
influences as well for us.

00:18:35.550 --> 00:18:39.540 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Well, it's kind
of like I said earlier to the group,

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:43.080
I was not going to be a musician.

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:45.610 position:56%
And I ended up going to a Cajun jam;

00:18:45.610 --> 00:18:46.910
therefore I play Cajun music.

00:18:46.910 --> 00:18:48.790
I still wonder if I would
have gone to a blues jam

00:18:48.790 --> 00:18:51.470
if I would have been
a blues musician.

00:18:51.470 --> 00:18:54.270 position:56%
I wasn't intending to be a musician.

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:55.870
Same thing with writing songs.

00:18:55.870 --> 00:19:00.230
I didn't intend to be a songwriter,
but when I did write my first song,

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:04.120
it sort of came out with this
country influence and possibly

00:19:04.120 --> 00:19:05.420
because that's what I grew

00:19:05.420 --> 00:19:08.010
up listening to, you
know, I'm guessing.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:12.520
But when you add these
guys to the mix,

00:19:12.520 --> 00:19:15.070
it's dance music I think
more than anything else.

00:19:15.070 --> 00:19:20.120
I grew up as a dancer instead of
a musician to that kind of music.

00:19:20.120 --> 00:19:22.590
So, when I started writing
songs, I wanted to be able

00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:24.650
to write songs that
you could dance to.

00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:30.320
So, we had that Cajun influence in
terms of dance ability to the song.

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:32.020
But when you add the steel guitar,

00:19:32.020 --> 00:19:34.390
it kind of brings in
that country genre.

00:19:34.390 --> 00:19:38.840
And then when Beau came into the
band, the two of them just latched

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:41.060
onto this, they sort of did it.

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:46.090
The song really didn't
have, it was in the making.

00:19:46.090 --> 00:19:47.390
It was creating.

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:51.250 position:56%
So, when I just put it out there and
just let those two guys take off,

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:56.250
it just kind of came with
this little Texas swing thing.

00:19:56.250 --> 00:20:02.040
And then when my son came on the
drums, he's got that, it's natural,

00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:03.340
it's genetic in him and he just,

00:20:03.340 --> 00:20:07.450
so it came to be this little
Louisiana swing honky tonk

00:20:07.450 --> 00:20:09.180
with a Cajun something or other.

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:10.870
I don't know what it is.

00:20:10.870 --> 00:20:12.420
It just is.

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:13.720
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:20:13.720 --> 00:20:16.860
Well, you play some of your own
songs but you also play songs

00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:19.050
that you've gotten from elsewhere.

00:20:19.050 --> 00:20:20.730
You know, cover songs
of various people.

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:22.400
So, how do you, what do
you look for in the song?

00:20:22.400 --> 00:20:24.110 position:56%
How do you find songs that you like?

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:26.780 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I have to feel it.

00:20:26.780 --> 00:20:28.330
That's the best way to explain it.

00:20:28.330 --> 00:20:31.010 position:56%
And my mom, she's all the time,
she's always sending me a text, "Oh,

00:20:31.010 --> 00:20:32.310
you should play this song.

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:33.610
You should do this.

00:20:33.610 --> 00:20:34.910
You should do this."

00:20:34.910 --> 00:20:36.900 position:56%
And I'll give it a try and sometimes
it'll, you know, it's a good song,

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:39.020
but I just, I don't feel it.

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:41.620
It's got to strike
something inside of me.

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:45.490
I don't know how else
to explain it than that.

00:20:45.490 --> 00:20:46.820
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: That's good.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:48.920
And in terms of writing
songs, I mean,

00:20:48.920 --> 00:20:50.560
you do write a lot of the songs.

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:55.660
What do you, how do things
strike you as song worthy?

00:20:55.660 --> 00:20:59.190
As being something you're
going to write a song about?

00:20:59.190 --> 00:21:01.440
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I don't
really think I write the songs.

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:04.660
I think I'm a vessel that
the songs come through.

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:08.790
There's not too many times where
I've sat down and said, "Today,

00:21:08.790 --> 00:21:10.560
I'm going to write a song."

00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:13.780
What happens is I'll be
doing something and then all

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:17.620
of the sudden I'll say, "I
need to go get my guitar."

00:21:17.620 --> 00:21:23.110
And then before I know it
there's a song that comes through.

00:21:23.110 --> 00:21:32.160
So, it might be something
I noticed, um, driving

00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:35.430
or something I heard somebody say.

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:38.690
I remember one time I was
cooking supper for my son

00:21:38.690 --> 00:21:42.350
and I was cooking a rice and
gravy and all of a sudden I had

00:21:42.350 --> 00:21:45.130
that feeling, I just had that
feeling of something was going

00:21:45.130 --> 00:21:48.370
on in my head and I said I
needed to go get my guitar.

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:51.640
So, I went in my room and I started
kind of doing this little melody

00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:55.380
that was there and the words were
coming and I'm writing this song.

00:21:55.380 --> 00:21:59.180
And then the next thing I know
my fire alarm was going off

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:02.240
and my house is full of smoke

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:04.850
and there's flames
coming up and I, you know,

00:22:04.850 --> 00:22:09.240
completely burnt the
supper, but I had this song.

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:14.160
And it was called, "Memories of
Clelia," And it was about a dad

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:16.280
who was contemplating suicide

00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:18.090
because he lost his
daughter and his wife.

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:21.690
Now, I don't remember
ever hearing about that

00:22:21.690 --> 00:22:23.370
or experiencing that or anything.

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:27.250
So, that's when I know it just,
you know, that was something that,

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:30.270
I was just the vessel
to come out of.

00:22:30.270 --> 00:22:31.570
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:22:31.570 --> 00:22:34.560
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: So, you know,
and like I said I might be,

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:37.460
the guy that I spoke with when
I first started writing songs,

00:22:37.460 --> 00:22:38.920
he told me just pay attention

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:41.060
and I really did take
those words to heart.

00:22:41.060 --> 00:22:43.090
And if you pay attention, there's
a lot of stuff to write about.

00:22:43.090 --> 00:22:44.390
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:22:44.390 --> 00:22:46.390
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: I think I
notice things and it kind of mulls

00:22:46.390 --> 00:22:49.100
over in my brain a
little bit and then

00:22:49.100 --> 00:22:50.570
when it's ready it will come out.

00:22:50.570 --> 00:22:52.170
That's how I do it.

00:22:52.170 --> 00:22:54.650
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah, well one
of the ones you sang today sort

00:22:54.650 --> 00:22:57.000
of sounded like that
because you said

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.300
that you heard this phrase
the house with no windows.

00:22:59.300 --> 00:23:00.600
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Oh, yeah.

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:02.470
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And you
thought, oh that's a good phrase,

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:03.770
and now you wrote a
whole song around that.

00:23:03.770 --> 00:23:05.070
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Absolutely.

00:23:05.070 --> 00:23:06.370
Yes.

00:23:06.370 --> 00:23:07.670
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, how
did that song come together?

00:23:07.670 --> 00:23:08.970
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Oh, I was
watching the documentary.

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:10.270
It was like three in the morning.

00:23:10.270 --> 00:23:11.660
I couldn't sleep.

00:23:11.660 --> 00:23:14.460
And I just thought that was the
most amazing thing, you know,

00:23:14.460 --> 00:23:16.060
like a house with no windows.

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:18.530
It's just -- it's so
vivid and visual.

00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:20.410
And I could see the imagery.

00:23:20.410 --> 00:23:25.350 position:56%
And I don't know if you've listened
to most of my songs they're kind of,

00:23:25.350 --> 00:23:27.130
I don't want to say
they're man hating songs

00:23:27.130 --> 00:23:30.320
but there's a theme
somewhere in there, you know?

00:23:30.320 --> 00:23:32.570
And it was just weird.

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:37.150
It's, like I said, I didn't intend
to sit down and write a song,

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:38.620
bashing, you know, anybody.

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:39.920
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:42.040
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: But
it just came out.

00:23:42.040 --> 00:23:43.340
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: One
of the great things

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:46.000
about that song I think is that,
you know, you say, you know,

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:49.720
one of your primary ways of
writing songs is to pay attention.

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:51.800
But that song if you don't pay
attention, if you just sort

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:55.050
of let it play, it sounds like
it's a sweet little love song.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:56.350
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

00:23:56.350 --> 00:23:57.650
Exactly.

00:23:57.650 --> 00:23:58.950
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: But you have
to be listening to the lyrics

00:23:58.950 --> 00:24:00.250
and know what is going on.

00:24:00.250 --> 00:24:01.850
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And sometimes
before I sing it I'll introduce it

00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:04.530
like that -- I'd like to sing
a little love song for you.

00:24:04.530 --> 00:24:07.480
But you have to be paying
attention to really catch it.

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:08.780
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:10.440
See if anybody notices what
you're really talking about.

00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:11.740
That's great.

00:24:11.740 --> 00:24:13.040
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

00:24:13.040 --> 00:24:14.520
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So,
that's sort of your,

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:18.210
so your songwriting process
is just sort of notice stuff

00:24:18.210 --> 00:24:19.830
or have stuff come to you.

00:24:19.830 --> 00:24:21.130
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah
[multiple speakers].

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:25.120
Right. And like I said,
and when these songs come,

00:24:25.120 --> 00:24:28.840
this is an amazing thing for me,
I don't partially write a song

00:24:28.840 --> 00:24:31.370
and put it away and then
come back to it or whatever.

00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:32.670
When they come, they just come.

00:24:32.670 --> 00:24:37.200
And within 10 to 20 minutes I'll
have a song and it's written.

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:38.500
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:41.520 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: And I may do a
little bit of tweaking on it but it,

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:44.640
you know, so that's why I say
I don't, I really don't feel

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:47.070
that I'm writing the song
if that makes any sense.

00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:48.370
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: I
know what you mean.

00:24:48.370 --> 00:24:49.670
Yeah.

00:24:49.670 --> 00:24:50.970
&gt;&gt; Richard Comeaux: We get to the
gate on Thursdays, we're like --

00:24:50.970 --> 00:24:52.580
she says T, I got a new song.

00:24:52.580 --> 00:24:53.880
And I'm setting up my stuff.

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:55.180
I'm like really?

00:24:55.180 --> 00:24:56.480
She said, "We're going
to do it tonight?"

00:24:56.480 --> 00:24:57.780
I said, "What do you mean?

00:24:57.780 --> 00:24:59.080
You're going to throw
me under the bus.

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:00.380
I never heard the dang thing."

00:25:00.380 --> 00:25:01.680
&gt;&gt; Yvette Landry: Yeah.

